  "text": "Verifying systems with unbounded resources is in general undecidable. For instance, the problem of verifying if a system of N (N can be arbitrarily large) concurrent processes satisfies a property is undecidable [CITATION_1] . Despite its complexity, the problem of verifying systems with arbitrarily large resources (e.g., parameterized systems with N processes, out-of-order processors with arbitrarily large reorder buffers, software programs with arbitrary large arrays) is of significant practical interest. Hence, in recent years, there has been a lot of interest in developing techniques based on model checking and deductive approaches for verifying such systems.",
